## 4. Selection states

How "this is the chosen one" reads visually. Different elements use
different conventions.

| Element | Treatment | Tokens |
|---|---|---|
| Checkbox (checked) | inner box fills with `surface-interactive-default`; checkmark mask becomes visible via `icon-inverse` | checkbox.css |
| Radio (selected) | outer ring stays, center dot fills with `icon-interactive`; label color → `text-interactive` | radio.css |
| Toggle (checked) | `surface-interactive-default` bg + `border-interactive`; thumb slides right | toggle.css |
| Tab (selected) | bottom border → `border-interactive`, text → `text-interactive` | tabs.css |
| Tile (selected) | bg → `surface-info-subtle`, border → `border-interactive` thickened to 2 px | tile.css |
| Chip (selected) | bg + border → `surface-interactive-active`; text → `text-inverse`; icons → `icon-inverse` | chip.css |
| Dropdown menu item (selected) | bg → `surface-interactive-subtle-active`; text → `text-interactive`; weight → `bold` | dropdown.css |
| Link (current-page, `aria-current="page"`) | text → `text-interactive-active` | link.css |
| Button (selected, `aria-selected="true"` or `[data-selected]`) | primary stays at its base fill; secondary / ghost gain a focus-ring-like outer ring | button.css |

**Pattern**: filled elements (chip, toggle, checkbox) go *more saturated*
on selection (interactive-default or interactive-active bg). Outlined
elements (tile, tabs, dropdown item, radio) gain a *colored marker*
(border + tinted bg, or a dot, or a bottom underline) and recolor text
to `text-interactive`.

