## 11. Selection vs. checked vs. active — naming guidance

Three words that are often confused:

| Term | Used by | What it means |
|---|---|---|
| **Checked** | checkbox, radio, toggle | Native HTML form-control selection state. Pair with `<input type="checkbox" checked>` / `aria-checked="true"`. |
| **Selected** | tabs, dropdown items, chip, tile | Non-form-control selection state. Pair with `aria-selected="true"` or `data-selected="true"`. |
| **Active** (as in current) | link, button (`[data-selected]`) | "This is the current page / current navigation target." Pair with `aria-current="page"` or `[data-selected]`. |
| **Active** (as in pressed) | every button, every interactive control during `:active` | Mouse-down state. Brief, ends on mouse-up. |

The two meanings of "Active" collide. When writing a spec or rule,
prefer "Pressed" for the mouse-down meaning and "Current" for the
selected-as-nav meaning. The CSS uses `:active` for pressed and
`aria-current` for current.

